Door-to-Door Paratransit Service

Door-to-Door Service must be provided on every trip; every time. This means all operators working on the platform, whether dedicated or non-dedicated (excluding TNC), are required to assist each customer from the facility, house or business door to the vehicle, and from the vehicle to the facility, house or business door, and ensuring all customers have SAFELY ENTERED the facility, house or business prior to leaving the location, thus preventing a “Leave Behind” situation that jeopardizes the safety of the rider.

 

How do I perform Door to Door Service?

·       Upon arrival at the pick-up location, the operator will exit the vehicle and proceed to the door and knock, ring the bell, or if a business or center enter the facility to ask for the customer by name. Under no circumstances should the operator require the customer to leave prior to the beginning of the ready-time window.

·       The operator will ask the customer if assistance (pushing manual wheelchair, offering an arm if customer has a vision disability, etc.) is needed. If yes, the operator shall follow the customer’s instruction and appropriately assist as requested. If not, the operator shall walk beside or behind the customer until they reach and enter through the threshold (drop-off) of the facility, house or business door or reach the door of the vehicle (pick up).

·       Upon arrival at the drop-off location, the operator will exit the vehicle and assist the customer from the vehicle to the threshold of the facility, house or business. The operator shall observe/ensure customer SAFELY ENTERS through the facility, house or business prior to leaving.

 

How do I prevent leaving a customer behind?

·       The operator shall immediately contact dispatch and make them aware of any instance in which they arrive at a stop and the customer cannot safely enter the facility, house or business.

 

·       The operator shall wait for instruction from the dispatcher who will advise on the best course of action to ensure the safety and well-being of the customer, and then adjust the remaining stops on the manifest, if appropriate.

·       The dispatcher will make a note on the instructions given in the notes section of the system.

 

     What are the consequences for not performing door to door or Leaving behind a rider?

·       Failing to perform door-to-door service or leaving a rider behind may result in a customer complaint, or even worse, an unforeseen unsafe event taking place that will be investigated by the Authority. This investigation could result in the Authority requesting the operator’s removal from providing services to their riding customers.

TriMet Criminal Background Check Consent

Form A

Oregon Revised Statutes (ORS) 267.237 provides TriMet access to Oregon State Police and Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) criminal records if the information is required to protect vulnerable Oregonians.

ORS 267.237(2) requires criminal records checks and fingerprinting of individuals who operate motor vehicles for the public and who are employed by mass transit districts or transportation districts or who provide transit service under a contract with the Accessible Transportation Programs (ATP). Screening applies to current employees, prospective employees (job applicants), and individuals under contract who transport the general public, including children, the elderly, individuals with disabilities, and clients eligible for ATP.

By my signature, I am consenting to the following:

·        My ability to provide transportation for the Accessible Transportation Program (ATP) is conditional upon the completion of a criminal history records check. I will not be qualified to provide transportation for the ATP if:

 

§  I refuse to complete an Oregon or federal criminal history records check, or provide my fingerprints;

§  I have a record of convictions or pending indictments of certain disqualifying criminal offenses; or

§  submit false information on the disclosure form.

·        TriMet uses all means available to it by law to complete a criminal history records check. A complete review of my criminal history record may include:

 

§  a criminal history records check through the Oregon State Police (OSP) and the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI), including fingerprint-based record checks;

§  using the information I disclose on the Criminal History Records Check Forms; and .

§  obtaining my driving record from any state’s Department of Motor Vehicles or equivalent agency.

·        I am entitled to review a copy of my personal Oregon criminal offender record as maintained and reported by the Oregon State Police. I may challenge any information that I believe to be inaccurate, incomplete, or kept in violation of any state or federal statute or act, through the Oregon State Police. Under federal law I am not entitled to review or obtain a copy of my FBI record. If I wish to challenge any FBI record information, including fingerprint-based records, I may do so through the Federal Bureau of Investigation. (Refer to Attachment B)

 

·        My completed criminal history records check and determination documentation will be securely maintained by TriMet. I am entitled to review my Oregon criminal offender record maintained by TriMet, after positive identification has been made.

·        I may have additional rights under Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964. I may obtain further information on my civil rights by inquiring at the Oregon Bureau of Labor and Industries.

 

·        If TriMet determines that I am not qualified to provide transportation for ATP customers, I may appeal that decision in accordance with Trimet’s Criminal Records Policy. Appeal procedures are emailed with disqualification notice. If you submit false information on the disclosure form, you are not eligible for the appeal process.

Policy:                        FUEL CARD RECEIPT, ACCEPTANCE, AND PASSTHROUGH POLICY

Effective Date:            January 1, 2025

 

Contractors authorized to receive fuel passthrough compensation as part of the FTA Funded services being provided are issued a Fuel Card with card ID that is linked specifically to a registered vehicle and the Operators Mobile Phone Number. This document is to verify that you understand your responsibilities and the policies regarding fuel passthrough and the use of your issued fuel card.

 

Contractor Acceptance Statements

 

·        I have been issued a fuel card with card ID, which authorizes me to fuel my vehicle only, in service to the network, as a part of the Fuel Passthrough allowance in my Services Agreement.

·        I understand that my personal mobile phone number being entered from my registered mobile device identifies me by name on a fuel report, and that I am accountable for all transactions made using my ID. Therefore, I will not share my Card ID, or my mobile device, with anyone. If I believe someone else knows my ID and my mobile device, I will immediately notify the company and/or leased fleet administrator.

·        I understand that the fuel card is not to be used for personal or non-business purposes. Using the fuel card for any purpose other than official business use will be considered misuse and subject to services agreement violation.

·        I understand that each time I use a fuel card I am required to completely fill the vehicle’s fuel tank and enter an accurate odometer reading each time to activate the card for use. This will allow the company to monitor fuel usage for accurate reimbursement. My failure to do this may result in a violation of my services agreement.

·        I understand that my fuel card expenditures will be reconciled against the miles recorded in service on the network. Any expenditures that exceed the passthrough allowance will be deducted from the monies owed to me for services.

·        I understand that each fuel card is assigned to a vehicle and can only be activated from a registered driver mobile phone for specific fueling purpose. My mobile phone device and number will work with any fuel card issued by the company as long as I have that specific card in my possession. I understand that it is against fuel passthrough policy to swap or share cards between vehicles or to use any card for other than the intended purpose.

1. Introduction This policy document establishes the principles, guidelines, and procedures governing [organization's] operations, ensuring compliance with legal, ethical, and professional standards. It applies to all employees, contractors, and stakeholders associated with the organization.

2. Purpose The purpose of this policy is to outline expectations, responsibilities, and the framework within which the organization operates. This policy ensures transparency, accountability, and efficiency in all activities.

3. Scope This policy applies to all employees, management, external partners, and stakeholders engaged with the organization, covering all operational, financial, and administrative activities.

4. Compliance and Legal Requirements All employees and stakeholders must comply with applicable local, national, and international laws. Non-compliance may result in disciplinary action, including termination or legal proceedings.

5. Code of Conduct

  • All employees shall uphold honesty, integrity, and professionalism in their conduct.

  • Harassment, discrimination, and unethical behavior will not be tolerated.

  • Confidential information must be protected and not disclosed without authorization.

6. Workplace Policies

  • Employees must adhere to workplace safety protocols and report any hazards.

  • Attendance and leave policies must be followed as per the organization’s HR guidelines.

  • The use of organization resources must be in line with approved purposes.

7. Data Protection and Privacy

  • All personal and sensitive data must be handled in compliance with data protection laws.

  • Unauthorized access, sharing, or misuse of confidential information is strictly prohibited.

8. Financial Management

  • All financial transactions must be recorded accurately and transparently.

  • Fraud, misappropriation of funds, or financial misconduct will lead to severe consequences.

  • Budgeting and expenditures must align with the organization’s financial policies.

9. Conflict of Interest

  • Employees and stakeholders must disclose any potential conflicts of interest.

  • Personal gain should not interfere with organizational responsibilities.

  • Any conflict must be resolved through the prescribed internal channels.

10. Reporting Violations

  • Any policy violations must be reported to the designated authority.

  • Whistleblowers will be protected against retaliation for reporting misconduct.

  • Investigations will be conducted fairly and confidentially.

11. Policy Review and Updates

  • This policy will be reviewed annually and updated as necessary.

  • Employees will be informed of any revisions and expected to comply with the latest version.

12. Conclusion By adhering to this policy, all stakeholders contribute to a professional, ethical, and legally compliant work environment. Failure to comply with these guidelines may result in disciplinary action or legal consequences.

1.      Pullout (PO) On Time.

2.      Be “On Time” for the 1st Pickup (PU)…within the first 5 minutes of the “early” window.

4.      Use the Tablet as Designed. It has turn-by-turn capabilities including voice activation. Transposing addresses to your own device will often result in a bad location being input.

5.      Use the PTT Device as Instructed. It is for service issues only and not for airing grievances and small talk. Other operators need assistance on the PTT Line.

6.      Never “arrive” any trip (PU or DO) unless you are physically present at the proper location. Tis is considered Fraud and is punishable by immediate dismissal from the Paratransit services.

7.      Follow the Established “No Show” Procedure to ensure that no one is left behind, missing their life sustaining appointments and treatments.

 

·         Arrive in the Window

·         Wait 1 Minute and Contact Dispatch for a “Courtesy Call”

Ø  Dispatch Reaches Out to Customer

Ø  Dispatch Verifies Location

Ø  Dispatch Confirms PU Window

·         Contact Dispatch If the Passenger Has Not Boarded After Five (5) Minutes

·         Wait for Dispatch to Authorize “No Show”

8.      When In Doubt…Contact the DDOT-PT Dispatcher for an advisory on the PTT Device.

9.      Practice Proper Passenger Assistance Techniques as demonstrated in the CTAA Passenger Assistance Orientation and Certification.

10.  Know the “3 Rs”:

·         Recognize…the Disability.

·         Respond…to the Customer.

·         Respect…the Person.

FIRST TRANSIT CODE OF CONDUCT FOR DRIVERS AND ATTENDANTS

 

As an operator or attendant I understand that I am providing Participants access to necessary medical care and public transportation, and that I have a heightened responsibility to ensure the privacy, security, and safety of the Participants who ride with me. I also understand that these trips are paid for by public healthcare funds and federal transit funds, and that fraud, waste, or abuse may subject me to criminal and/or civil liability. By signing below, I agree to the following:

 

I will...

I will NOT…

Identify myself by name and company at the beginning of every trip.

Solicit or accept controlled substances, alcohol, or medications from Participants.

Keep my identification clearly visible while on duty.

Solicit or accept money (including tips or gifts) from Participants.

Provide Participants with dignified boarding assistance to the seating portion of the vehicle.

Use any alcohol, narcotics, illegal or prescription drugs, whatsoever, or any over-the-counter medication that impairs my ability to my job.

Keep the Participant’s safety at the heart of all I do.

Enter the home or residence of a Participant while on duty.

Be cognizant of and sensitive to Participants’ needs,

cultural diversity, and communication requirements.

Make sexually explicit comments, solicit sexual favors, or engage in sexual activity while performing my job duties.

Be courteous, patient, and helpful to all Participants.

Wear any type of headphones while on duty.

Be neat and clean in appearance while on duty.

Transport more passengers than my vehicle’s capacity.

Notify my employer/provider if a Participant has been assigned to the wrong level of service.

Operate the vehicle with passenger doors in the open position.

Notify my employer/provider (or First Transit) if a Participant appears to be going to a non-medical service.

Operate the vehicle with inoperable passenger doors or other identified safety issue.

Park so that Participants do not have to cross streets to

reach my vehicle or the destination.

Refuel while a Participant is on board.

Appropriately use the wheelchair securement devices

and store mobility devices, when needed.

Transport a Participant to any location other than what is provided on the Trip Order/Dispatch.

Immediately notify my employer/provider if I receive notice of license suspension, cancellation, or revocation.

Transfer a Participant from one vehicle to another during transport, except in the case of mechanical breakdown, accident, or other emergency.

Immediately notify my employer/provider of any traffic violation/citation, even if not on duty at the time.

Abandon a Participant in the vehicle.

Abide by the HIPPA regulations, protect the privacy and security of Participants’ information, and report any potential security incidents to my employer/provider and/or First Transit immediately.

Place or accept calls or texts at any time during transport, unless safely parked.

A Motor Vehicle Record (MVR), also known as a Driver Record, is a document that provides details about a driver’s history, including traffic violations, accidents, and license status. In California, you can obtain your MVR online through the California Department of Motor Vehicles (DMV) website. Follow the steps below to request and download your MVR.

Step 1: Visit the California DMV Website
Go to the California DMV's official website:
https://www.dmv.ca.gov

Step 2: Log Into Your DMV Account
If you have an existing DMV online account, log in using your credentials. If you don’t have an account, you will need to create one by providing:

Your California driver’s license number
The last four digits of your Social Security Number (SSN)
Your date of birth
Step 3: Request Your Driver Record
Once logged in, navigate to the “Driver Record Request” section.
Verify your identity by confirming your driver’s license details.
Review the disclosure agreement and accept the terms.
Step 4: Pay the Required Fee
The fee for an online MVR request is $2.00 (subject to change).
You can pay using a credit or debit card.
Step 5: Download Your MVR
Once the payment is processed, your MVR will be available for immediate download in PDF format.
Be sure to save or print a copy for your records.
Additional Information
Processing Time: The online request is processed instantly, and you can access your MVR immediately.
Eligibility: Your driver’s license must be valid and not suspended or expired to request an online record.
Alternative Methods: If you prefer, you can request your MVR by mail or in person at a local DMV office.
For more details, visit the California DMV website or contact their customer support.

Your motor vehicle report (MVR) is a record of your driving history, kept by your state's Department of Motor Vehicles. Also called a motor vehicle record, your MVR lists citations, accidents, DUI convictions, and any other violations that are a part of your driving history that help determine your viability in transporting riders with disabilities, safely. MVR's are run by a 3rd Party who will seek your permission to begin the process in a separate communication. Examples of adverse records: Driver’s License Suspension with the Past 5 Years/ Excesses amounts of points/ Less than 3 Years of being a licensed driver. If you feel that you may have any of these on your records, please consult your advisor. All candidate rights are considered and protected by applicable federal, state, and local regulations.
